</div></div>

<!-- ░░ LAYMAN ░░ -->
<div class="ov-only">
<section class="dsec ov-intro"><div class="wrap">
  <div class="sec-head"><div><div class="eyebrow">In layman’s terms</div><h2>Credit, in plain words.</h2></div><span class="fresh-tag">data through {dataThrough}</span></div>
  <div class="kpibar ov-kpi">
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-k">Cost of risky borrowing</div><div class="kpi-v sm">Low — stretched</div><div class="kpi-meta"><span class="vt">baseline</span></div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-k">EM government risk (EMBI)</div><div class="kpi-v">{fmt(byNo['2.1'])}</div><div class="kpi-meta"><span class="vt">current</span></div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-k">Cash hiding in money funds</div><div class="kpi-v">{fmt(byNo['2.2'])}</div><div class="kpi-meta"><span class="vt">current</span></div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-k">Are lenders nervous?</div><div class="kpi-v sm">Not yet — at the edges</div><div class="kpi-meta"><span class="vt">read</span></div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="ov-beats">
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">What credit is doing</div><p>“Credit” is the market for lending to companies and governments, and <b>spreads</b> are the extra interest lenders charge for the risk. Right now spreads are <b>low</b> — lenders are relaxed — but stretched: there isn’t much cushion if things turn.</p></div>
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">Why it matters</div><p>Cheap credit funds everything — buybacks, building, payrolls. When spreads blow out, financing dries up fast, and it usually <b>hits the stock market next</b>. Credit is the canary.</p></div>
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">Who’s exposed</div><p>In the current Gulf-conflict episode, {ovWinTxt} <b>benefit</b> (safe-haven cash, a strong dollar), while {ovLoseTxt} <b>suffer</b> (a dollar squeeze). The pain is mostly at the <i>government/funding</i> edge so far, not big US companies.</p><a class="ov-link" href="/markets/credit#catalysts">See the full winners &amp; losers →</a></div>
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">What’s driving it now</div><p>Interest rates (which set the base cost), the slow <b>default cycle</b> (how many borrowers fail), and a <b>dollar-funding squeeze</b> from the Gulf conflict. No single cause — we name them all, including what we can’t explain.</p></div>
    <div class="ov-beat"><div class="ovb-h">What to watch</div><p>High-yield (“junk”) spreads breaking wider, rising downgrades and defaults, money flooding out of bond funds, and whether central banks open <b>dollar swap lines</b> to relieve the squeeze.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="ov-foot"><span class="dconf medium">Overall confidence: medium</span><a class="cta-frame cta-h" href="/markets/credit">Open the Analyst view — full data, tables &amp; sources →</a></div>
  <p class="tnote">Hover any <span class="gloss" data-def="A specialist term, explained in plain language when you hover.">underlined term</span> for a plain definition. Research and analysis, not investment advice.</p>
</div></section>
</div>

